Preheat your oven to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel). Pop the wedges onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{2%tsp}, season with @salt{pinch} and @ground black pepper{} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary. When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, about ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Pick the @mint{1/2%bunch}(leaves picked and finely chopped) from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks). Put half the mint in a large #bowl{}. Add the @panko breadcrumbs{10%g} and @water{2%tbsp} for the breadcrumbs, then mix to combine. Add the @lamb mince{200%g}. Season with @salt{1/4%tsp} and pepper then mix together with your hands. Roll the mince into even-sized balls, then shape into 1cm thick burgers (1 per person).

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

> TIP: The burgers will shrink a little during cooking.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the burgers to the pan and fry until browned on the outside and cooked through, about ~{12-14%minutes} in total. Carefully turn them every ~{3-4%minutes} and lower the heat if needed.

> IMPORTANT: The burgers are cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

While the burgers cook, halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g} and pop them into a medium bowl. Halve the @red chilli{1/2}(deseeded and finely chopped) lengthways, deseed and finely chop. Add the chilli (careful, it's hot - add less if you don't like heat), @cider vinegar{15%ml}, @olive oil{2%tbsp} for the dressing and remaining mint to the tomatoes. Season with salt and pepper, then mix together and set aside.

Halve the @burger buns{2} and grate the @mature cheddar cheese{30%g}. When the burgers are cooked, remove the pan from the heat. Carefully place the cheese on top of the burgers. Cover with a #lid{} (or #foil{}) then set aside, off the heat, for ~{3-4%minutes} for the cheese to melt. Meanwhile, pop the burger buns onto a baking tray and place on the middle shelf of your oven. Warm for ~{3-4%minutes}.

When everything is ready, pop the warmed burger buns on your plates. Lay a cheesy lamb burger on top of each bun base and sandwich on the bun lid. Serve with the wedges and chimichurri tomato salad alongside. Enjoy!